segments.text: the College of Education since 1977.

OK, today is October the 21st, and I'm interviewing Dr. David Erlandson, who is the head of the Educational Administration Department at Texas A&M and has been with the College of Education since 1977.
And what we're going to talk about, I guess, is the changes that have occurred since you have been at Texas A&M.

how you think these changes have impacted the college, what do you feel maybe were the causes, and a little bit about what or how you think the college is achieving its mission of teaching research and service, whether it has changed from the previous administration to now.
So just a general, just how you feel.
Actually, I guess a lot of the things are in the archives, but people's perceptions and feelings are not.
And that's what I'd like for you to share is certain things that maybe I wouldn't find in any of the documents.
OK. And I'll take a few notes, too.
OK.

When I think back over the past 10 years, now, in many ways, when I first came here 10 years ago, it was, I guess, a little bit of a culture shock, because I come from New York City, Queens College, and the City University of New York.
And it would have probably been hard to have chosen a place that was more opposite.
from what Queens College was than Texas University, Texas A&M University.
In fact, I can remember somebody asking me after I'd been here about two or three years, and I met a gentleman from Boston when I was down visiting interns in Houston.
And he knew something about Queens College, and he knew something about Texas A&M.
He was, as I recall, he consulted Texas Instruments and Computers.
And he asked me what I thought, or he asked me how I would compare the two institutions.
And I thought about it just a moment, and I said to him, well, I said, compare the two institutions.
The best thing about Texas A&M is that there's no graffiti on the walls.
I said the worst thing about Texas A&M is that there's no graffiti on the walls.
Okay.
Because I think one of the things that, you know, as I came from teaching in college ten years ago, I was certainly impressed by the cleanliness, almost the squeaky clean nature of the institution.
I also was impressed by the, if you want, the
Lack of fertility of thought, the almost stability in the thought of many people, students and faculty.

In fact, I guess one of the other pieces of culture shock that I first noted when I first came in my first class, I noticed that when I began speaking, everybody was writing everything down that I said.
And if I gave an assignment, there are no questions about the assignment.
They just went ahead and did it to the best of their ability.
It's quite a contrast from Queens College, where anything I said was challenged.
Every assignment I gave was, is that really the best thing?
And what's the educational intent of this?
And that is very different.
So what do you attribute that to?
sterility of thought, as you put it, in the college?
What do you think would cost that?

Well, I think the traditions of engineering on the one hand, the dominance of engineering, where they prefer specific, clear answers in which they're trained in a way to come up with solutions and the best solution within relatively short periods of time.
That, I think, possibly also the military tradition,
where there is always somebody in charge and you take the orders from above.
I think that was part of it.
Even though this was an education?
Even though this was an education, yes.
I think it spilled over throughout the university.
I'll get back to a couple of the reasons.
Also, I think that it was true in education, but one of the differences I noted, for instance, between here and Queens also is
If I give a written assignment at Queens, I may or may not get any assignments I ask for on time.
Those that came in, some of them would be done sloppily.
Some would be absolutely brilliant, perceptive, creative.
Once I got at Texas A&M, tended all more to look alike.
They were on to them.
They were correct, often not extremely creative.
Now, this is an assumption on my part to a great extent.
I think that much of it goes to the institution, also to the clientele, the kind of student that it was drawing and what students were looking for in coming to Texas A&M.
But I think also if you look at the administration,
and the faculty that were there and had been there for many years, you got a similar kind of focus and emphasis.
One of the things that I liked very much about Texas A&M after having been in New York is that they had a nicely streamlined administrative structure.
There wasn't a lot of
burgeoning, empty, deadening bureaucracy, in the worst sense of the word.
Since I've been at Texas A&M, I've never felt that if I had a question about something or if I wanted to do something, I always could get a clear, definitive answer.
That may be less true now than it was then, but I think we are getting something of a bureaucracy in the bad sense of the term.
But it was very, the change of command, where you would go for answers, where you would go for approval was very clear.
Quite a contrast to New York.
You never know who to ask.
You send up a formal request through channels and you never know what happened to it.
You never know what decision maker at what level cut the thing off or if it just disappeared.
It was very, very frustrating.
Here was much better in that respect.
Who recruited you, Brandon?
Did you apply yourself or did somebody actually
Oh, I think that if I had to name one person, it probably would be John Hoyle.
I had known John for a number of years through mutual endeavors in the National Conference of Professors of Educational Administration.
And I would say he was.
He also played with me with Paul Henshaw Lane and with some of the others.
Then my application, I took it from there.
I was anxious to get out of City University of New York because they were facing bankruptcy.
And in fact, they had just given us a furlough for a couple of weeks without pay in order to help solve a little bit of the problem.
And it didn't look like it.
It wasn't very encouraging.
I was looking around, and this being a possibility, so I was very eager to take it.
How long after you were here did you become department head?
Seven years after I was here.
I became department head in 1984.
As I say, I think that some of the people who were here, like certainly Dean Huber in the College of Education, was very much nuts and bolts, no-nonsense administrator.
He liked to keep his lines of control.
very clean.
He liked to keep them all in his own hands.
We, at that time in 1977, we just had a new president who was a former Aggie, Jarvis Miller, who also projected the same kind of image.
And I think at that time the institution was still fostering that.
And things have changed gradually, I think, throughout the university.
I mean, right now we have a very, very different kind of president who, you know, I think by nearly anyone's account probably is not a very efficient administrator.
He comes across much more as the intellectual leader, as the stimulator.
That's a vastly different kind of setting.
I think there are some negatives to that.
I think right now the bureaucracy probably is growing somewhat.
It's hard to get the specific answer.
It's hard to always determine exactly where decisions are made.
Within, are you speaking about the college or the whole university?
Within the university right now.
Within the college, being a much smaller kind of an operation, that hasn't been true.
Of course, we had our change in 1980 when Dean Corrigan came.
And once again, a night and day change.
A person who did not see all the lines of authority coming out of his own office.

or tying back to his own office, no need for reporting every small detail, much more of a willingness to give responsibility to others, delegate to that responsibility, and allow others to pursue the mission as they saw it in the way that they saw it, and to build the college on that kind of a trust relationship.
Couple of things as we parallel it with the university.

One, being a member of a very small department, a relatively small department in contrast to the others in the College of Education, two of which are much larger, is that bureaucracy as such has always been less of a problem for us.
And also, there's another piece, too.
You never see the bureaucracy.
when you're right in the middle of it.

And one of the things that Dean Corrigan did early, sort of, if you want a new piece of bureaucracy introduced, was his steering committee for fostering educational inquiry, his own inquiry effort, which was sort of a loose kind of bureaucracy, but nevertheless was another kind of a structure sort of superimposed upon the operating structure of departments.
Did you find a little resistance to that?
Oh, yes.
Yeah, there was a lot of resistance.
Quiet, not loud, but there was a simple foot dragging, probably still is.
I guess there probably still is, much less now.
However, one of the reasons that I guess that I never felt the weight of that bureaucracy is because I was always part of that from the beginning.
When you first put together the Steering Committee for Fostering Educational Inquiry, I was invited to be the EDAD representative on it,
And then later I chaired that committee.
So I never saw it.
Now as department head, sitting on the policy committee, we're making the decisions.
I'm not entirely aware of the bureaucracy as it's built up or as others may feel it.
I think I've got a fairly good feel for how it operates in our department and how our professors feel it.
And I say fairly good because it certainly is not perfect.
But because we have a relatively small department, there are just 11 full-time members, I can get pretty good face-to-face feedback.
In the two really large departments, curriculum instruction or C&I, I know that they've got, you know, assistant department and heads of programs and all that sort of thing.
And I would think that you might find the responses there
very different.
Was there a real big shift when this came about from the mission of the college?
Did it change very drastically from Hubert as far as emphasis on research?
Because that seemed to be Corrigan's big thing as soon as he came in with his inquiry.
And how was it in place before that?
Well, yeah.
In specific language, I don't think of what the mission was stated.
or as it was supposed by the two deans, I think was probably less different than what it actually was in operation.
Dean Hubert also believed in research and he worked hard to bring good researchers into the College of Education
and once they got here to give them considerable resources so that they could do their work.
The biggest difference there was that his definition of research was much more restricted.
I think also his definition of service may have been somewhat more restricted.

Having come up himself in the public schools of Texas and worked with TA, I think in terms of what he envisioned for ways that the university could interact with schools was pretty much a function of what he had experienced himself and the types of things.
The state of differences weren't that different.
The operational differences was.

One other piece of operational difference is that when Dean Huber took over the College of Education, when General Rutter brought him here to Texas A&M, he was determined he was going to build the College of Education on hard state money.
There are a lot of horror stories from around the country of
colleges of education particularly, as well as other colleges, but colleges of education particularly that haven't built on soft money, there's grant money.
And then when the grant money was gone, they collapsed.
There was all sorts of acrimony.
There was people losing their jobs, et cetera.
And Frank Hubert saw, I think, that his job to build a college of education, to build a strong college of education, was to build it entirely on hard money.
I think that was a wise decision, because I think if it had been done any other way, the College of Education would not have received the strong foundation that it did while he was here.
How much is that true today?
Is it still on hard money?
Much less.
Much less.
We're still on much more hard money than most colleges of education and comparable universities are.
We're bringing in, I believe, considerably more grant money.
That's something you can check out.
I couldn't actually quote you the figures, but I think we're doing considerably better, even though the funding sources have decreased.
I see one of the things that Dean Healer would never want to have, he would never want one of his professors supported with grant money.
He wanted them all to be paid with state funds.

which has some powerful implications, because it means that, OK, you can go ahead and conduct this project, get this grant, do this research for this grant that you want to do, but you've still got to teach your class load, full class load, because that's what we're paying you for.
The rest is sort of fun and games.
And I think Oregon has seen the research, the inquiry, much more of a central focus than Dean here or Tim.
Was there as much collaboration between departments as there is now, or is there more now?
How does that stand in the two?
That's a good question.
I think there's probably more collaboration now than there was, to a great extent because of the inquiry structure that cuts across departments.
And that was Gene Bergen's.

expectation in other ways though i would hypothesize that there may be less there may be less now uh because uh when the college of edu college of education of course came out of the department of education and psychology and uh for a while during its maturation and growth
College of Education was probably really little more than a large department.
I mean, they were formal divisions now with department heads, et cetera.
But some of the departments were, like ours, was really very, very small before we started adding members.
I mean, just very small.
And it means that the collegial relationships were necessarily developed with other people.
And if you go back with, what, the old-timers,

in the College of Education, particularly some of those who were around in the last days of the Department of Education and Psychology, they still have a lot of personal ties and a style of operation that harks back to that.
And I think new members of the College of Education don't have that same type of thing.
People when I came in 77, which was, you know,
considerably after, a considerable time after the College of Education was formed, I still by necessity formed a lot of, got to know and began working with people in the other departments.
Now, I'm not sure that that's true.
The, I would say we have some departments, some of our professors who except for
Maybe the formal requirements of some particular committee work, or maybe working jointly on a pro-seminar, or some specific assignment, have practically no contact at all outside of the department.
That's probably even more true for the large departments.
I'm concerned, for instance, with one of our new professors, with Yvonne Gonzalez in the Principal Center, that she doesn't have enough contact with all the people
in the college, basically.
There were other little things, too.
It's just an aside, but I think it's a function of the same thing.
Speaking for myself, and so I'm pointing to the finger of myself, I haven't been to a White Alta Kappa meeting in a local chapter in a long time.
But I noticed in looking over our slate of officers for this year, I think there are two assistant professors
from the college on there.
Maybe two or three, but about that number.
Most of the people are either graduate students or not related to the college.

When I first came here, it was the Don Barkers and the Glenn Johnsons, John Hoyles, and the others, the key people in the College of Education, the key professors, who were also part of the capital larger picture
It seems to be less of a concern.
Well, for instance, last night, the local part of the chapter met, and Ken Kaepernick was speaking.
I always enjoy hearing from Ken.
He's always very candid.
And I debated it for a while, and then just decided I needed time more for other kinds of things.
Well, that's tragic in a way.
I think we're in danger of losing something, a broader scope.
I mean, the better things, of course, for me, have become things tied more directly to administration and what we're doing.
In a sense, that's good, because we're doing some very exciting things.
We're also losing that overall view.
And that's unfortunate that that occurred.
In your department specifically, do you feel that the department is

much more to service than it is, of course, teaching is everybody, that's one of the primary goals, I guess, in every department, first and foremost, but there's some departments that are very, are leaning very much towards the research, and I guess psychology, educational psychology would be one that's heavy, heavy into the research, and is there a balance within departments as to, you know, because I would think that administration
It would have to be more service, would it not?
We're very, very heavy into service.
In fact, I think if you look right now at our best research efforts, the research efforts are flowing out of the service.
Now, that's not entirely a one-way street.
I think some of the service efforts are also flowing out of the research we're doing.
But I would say that
the more powerful drive has to be coming out of the service and motivation.
Part of that is because, well, we now have two quasi-independent centers within the community education center and the principal center.
Both of them, of course, take their existence from the fact that they're service centers.
And research is always in the support of service by definition of what they're doing.
That's what causes it.
We have some research isn't, for instance.
I would say it's going the other way.
Harold Hawkins' current work with his interface between learning and school plant, that study he's conducting, I would say it's primarily research driven.
It has obvious service implications, but it's research good.
What we're doing with the management profile, myself and John Hoyle, I'm not sure which is in the driver's seat on that.
I think one shifted from one point to another, and that's maybe the balance between the two.
Very good.
Now, how do you think or feel that the university or the college is perceived by outsiders outside
even A&M outside of the state.
I know you do a lot of consulting, and you're visible in a lot of national organizations, and a lot of your people are.
What is the general feeling as you travel around and participate in all this?
How do they see our College of Education in relation to the others?
Well, much, much better than they did 10 years ago.
There's no question that we've risen in the esteem of observers from around the nation.
I'm getting many more personal calls and direct inquiry about our students to fulfill professor's positions in other universities.
In some areas, the service areas,
I think that we really stand out for, even among those other institutions that are also service oriented.
I think the things we're doing there are exemplary.
The research, well I think if you looked at the, now this is, I'm speaking for educational administration, it's probably less true in educational psychology, but if you went back to the

classical researchers in the last 30 years, the positivistic researchers that have dominated educational administrations as well as all of education, I would say they would look at what we're doing and think we're doing a pretty good job, but are not overly impressed by it.
Yeah, I think that would be a fair estimate.

uh they don't think we're doing any we don't look at some things that we've done and like them very well but other things that they're just not not super super impressed uh but on the other hand uh it's one of my doctoral students who had a final defense in uh august and will graduate in december uh picked up by lsu uh phyllis lot naturalistic research had been vacated by bill greenfield and we're perhaps
and maybe the top name in that area in the educational administration.
I think that's a...
Okay, now we talked a little bit about the past and what's going on right now.
My study will cover all three with just a little bit of looking towards the future.
How do you feel from when you're sitting as head of your department that the college is going, say, not just
the year 2000, which everybody seems to be talking about right now, but even a little beyond that?
I think one of the things that is going to have to happen, I have to say have to happen because, no, it's not going to have to happen.
I can go either one or two ways.
One of the things that ought to happen, I guess it's better to say, is that we need to become much more focused in our mission.
One of the things I think that emerged with the new era that was actually given by Dean Corrigan was the feeling that we could do anything we wanted and we could do everything we wanted.
The latter may be true, probably isn't, but it may be true.
Excuse me, the former may be true.
probably the latter definitely is not true.
There's no way that we can do everything that we would like to do.
We're tired just having done what we've done and we've wasted a lot of effort.
I think we need to define what it is we do well and do that.
I think part of what's occurred in the past has been that we've been trying to establish that name, that reputation.
I think we've pretty well done that now.
People know who we are.
I think now is the time for us to refine and do things on a smaller scale extremely well.
And I think that applies across the board.
For instance, in teacher training, we're now preparing more teachers than any other institution, more science teachers.
In Texas, more science teachers than any other institution in the nation.
Maybe we need to cut back.
Maybe since we can't do everything, we just ought to make the best of it.
And we literally do the best.
And I think in administration, that's true.
Rather than trying to do new things, I think that we need now to focus, to refine.
The same with the management profile.
It's going places.
Rather than doing anything new, we need to refine, make that better, learn how to improve on that.
I'd say the same thing would be for all the things that we're trying to do.
In every department or just your department?
I'm saying for our department now, but I think that the same thing holds true across the college.
Since the college is geared or is called, you know, the research, a research center or university or whatever, is there pressure on each college to focus on the research exclusively?
There's not a lot of research here.
There's not a lot of pressure here.
I think research occurs, and we're conscious of it, and we want it to occur, but there isn't a lot of research.
I think there is a pretty fair amount of research.
There isn't a lot of pressure on research.
There probably could be more research.
Not all of our professors, either in our department or I'm sure across the college,
are as productive research as they could be and ought to be.
I know that that's true for our department.
But nevertheless, we have some very, very good pieces of research coming up, excellent pieces.
Professor research and doctoral dissertation research.
But the pressure is not there.
Just by way of contrast,
